=========================================================
MULTIPLE INHERITANCE IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Multiple Inheritance is an OOP mechanism in which a class inherits from
more than one base class.

In simple words:

One Derived Class
          ↓
Inherits from
          ↓
Multiple Base Classes

=========================================================
SYNTAX
=========================================================

class Base1
{
};

class Base2
{
};

class Derived : public Base1, public Base2
{
};

=========================================================
DIAGRAM
=========================================================

        Base1        Base2
           \          /
            \        /
             \      /
              Derived

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED MULTIPLE INHERITANCE?
=========================================================

Sometimes an object naturally possesses features from multiple classes.

Examples:

SmartPhone
   IS-A Camera
   IS-A MusicPlayer

MultiFunctionPrinter
   IS-A Printer
   IS-A Scanner

FlyingCar
   IS-A Car
   IS-A Aircraft

Multiple Inheritance allows code reuse from multiple base classes.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Printer
{
public:
    void print()
    {
        cout << "Printing\n";
    }
};

class Scanner
{
public:
    void scan()
    {
        cout << "Scanning\n";
    }
};

class MultiFunctionPrinter :
        public Printer,
        public Scanner
{
};

int main()
{
    MultiFunctionPrinter m;

    m.print();
    m.scan();
}

Output:

Printing
Scanning

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    int x;
};

class B
{
public:
    int y;
};

class C : public A, public B
{
public:
    int z;
};

Memory Layout:

C Object
------------------
A::x
------------------
B::y
------------------
C::z
------------------

Derived object contains:

Base1 Part + Base2 Part + Derived Part

=========================================================
CONSTRUCTOR CALL ORDER
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    A()
    {
        cout << "A\n";
    }
};

class B
{
public:
    B()
    {
        cout << "B\n";
    }
};

class C : public A, public B
{
public:
    C()
    {
        cout << "C\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    C obj;
}

Output:

A
B
C

Rule:

Base constructors execute in the order of inheritance declaration.

=========================================================
DESTRUCTOR ORDER
=========================================================

Output:

C
B
A

Rule:

Destructors execute in reverse order.

=========================================================
FUNCTION NAME CONFLICT (AMBIGUITY)
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    void show()
    {
        cout << "A\n";
    }
};

class B
{
public:
    void show()
    {
        cout << "B\n";
    }
};

class C : public A, public B
{
};

int main()
{
    C obj;

    // obj.show();   // ERROR
}

Compilation Error:

Reference to show() is ambiguous.

=========================================================
HOW TO RESOLVE AMBIGUITY?
=========================================================

Use Scope Resolution Operator.

=========================================================

obj.A::show();

obj.B::show();

=========================================================

Output:

A
B

=========================================================
ACCESS SPECIFIERS IN MULTIPLE INHERITANCE
=========================================================

class C :
      public A,
      protected B,
      private D
{
};

Each base class can have its own inheritance mode.

=========================================================
ADVANTAGES OF MULTIPLE INHERITANCE
=========================================================

1. Code Reusability
2. Combines multiple functionalities
3. Better modeling of real-world entities
4. Reduces code duplication
5. Supports interface implementation

=========================================================
DISADVANTAGES OF MULTIPLE INHERITANCE
=========================================================

1. Ambiguity
2. Increased Complexity
3. Tight Coupling
4. Diamond Problem
5. Difficult Maintenance

=========================================================
MOST FAMOUS PROBLEM
=========================================================

Diamond Problem

            A
           / \
          /   \
         B     C
          \   /
           \ /
            D

D gets TWO copies of A.

Causes:
• Ambiguity
• Duplicate Data
• Memory Overhead

Solution:
Virtual Inheritance

=========================================================
MULTIPLE INHERITANCE AND INTERFACES
=========================================================

Multiple inheritance is commonly used for interfaces.

=========================================================

class IPrinter
{
public:
    virtual void print() = 0;
};

class IScanner
{
public:
    virtual void scan() = 0;
};

class MultiFunctionPrinter :
        public IPrinter,
        public IScanner
{
public:
    void print() override
    {
        cout << "Printing\n";
    }

    void scan() override
    {
        cout << "Scanning\n";
    }
};

=========================================================

This is a very common real-world use of Multiple Inheritance.

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Multiple Inheritance?

Answer:
Multiple inheritance allows a class to inherit from more than one base
class.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Why do we need Multiple Inheritance?

Answer:
To combine functionalities from multiple classes and improve code reuse.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Does C++ support Multiple Inheritance?

Answer:
YES.

Java classes do not support it directly due to the Diamond Problem.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. What are the disadvantages of Multiple Inheritance?

Answer:
• Ambiguity
• Complexity
• Diamond Problem
• Tight Coupling

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. How do you resolve function ambiguity?

Answer:
Using Scope Resolution Operator.

Example:

obj.A::show();
obj.B::show();

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. What is the biggest issue with Multiple Inheritance?

Answer:
Diamond Problem.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. How do you solve the Diamond Problem?

Answer:
Virtual Inheritance.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. In what order are constructors called?

Answer:
Base classes are constructed in the order they appear in the inheritance
list.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. In what order are destructors called?

Answer:
Reverse order of construction.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Multiple Inheritance is a feature of C++ in which a class inherits from
more than one base class. It allows combining functionalities from
multiple classes and improves code reuse. However, it can introduce
ambiguity and the Diamond Problem, making the design more complex. These
issues can be managed using scope resolution and virtual inheritance.

